On the UAP, you can configure the IP addresses of up to four D-Link Wireless Switches that can manage it. In order to manage the AP, the switch and AP must discover each other.

Secure Shell (SSH) is a program that provides access to the D-Link UAP CLI from a remote host, SSH is more secure than Telnet for remote access. From the SSH page, you can enable or disable SSH access to the system.

The radio frequency (RF) broadcast channel defines the portion of the radio spectrum that the radio on the access point uses for transmitting and receiving. The range of available channels for an access point is determined by the IEEE 802.11 mode (also referred to as band) of the access point.
General global configurations

If you use SNMP to manage the Wireless Switch, you can configure the SNMP agent on the switch to send traps to the SNMP manager on this page. When an AP is managed by a switch, the switch learns about through updates from the APs and delivers traps for them.
The Distributed Tunneling mode, also known as AP-AP tunneling mode, is used to support L3 roaming for wireless clients without forwarding any data traffic to the wireless switch.
From the CP Global Configuration page, you can control the administrative state of the CP feature and configure global settings that affect all captive portals configured on the switch.
From the SNMP Trap Configuration page, you can configure whether SNMP traps are sent from the CP or not and to specify captive portal events that will generate a trap.

The wireless network list shows all the wireless networks configured on the switch. The first 16 networks are created by default. You can modify the default networks, but you cannot delete them. Multiple networks can have the same SSID.

The DHCP address pool defines the range of the IP address that can be assigned to stations in the network. A Dynamic Pool allows wireless stations to receive an available IP with lease time control. If needed or required in the network, the device is capable of acting as a DHCP server.
System Configuration provides some general configurations which includes network settings, account settings and the settings of Telnet as well as SSH.
From the Wireless Configuration page, you can set primary SSID of different wireless band for each device.

From the Security Configuration page, you can set authentication mode of different wireless band for each device.

The device supports up to four multiple Service Set Identifiers. You can set the Primary SSID. The SSID’s factory default setting is dlink. The SSID can be easily changed to connect to an existing wireless network or to establish a new wireless network.
The Wireless Schedule Settings window is used to add and modify scheduling rules on the device.
You can add a bunch of MAC addresses of wireless devices for different wireless band to enable the access control of the configured device.

You can create multiple AP profiles on the wireless switch to customize APs. For each AP profile, you can configure the following features: Profile settings (Name, Hardware Type ID, Wired Network Discovery VLAN ID), Radio settings, SSID settings, QoS configuration.
